Dynamic Programming (DP): Full Explanation

Dynamic Programming is an optimization technique used when:

A problem can be split into overlapping subproblems

Those subproblems have optimal substructure

DP avoids recomputation by storing results and reusing them.

DP = Recursion + Memoization (Top-Down)
OR
DP = Tabulation (Bottom-Up)

🚀 1. When to Use DP?

You should think DP when:

✔ The problem can be expressed as:
f(n) depends on f(smaller values)

✔ Same subproblems repeat

(Overlapping subproblems)

✔ There is a choice

(Max/min/count/etc.)

✔ Greedy won’t work

(Decision depends on future choices)

Classic trigger words in interviews:

"maximum"

"minimum"

"number of ways"

"longest"

"shortest"

"at least"

"optimal"

🚀 2. Two DP Techniques
A) Top-Down (Memoization)

Write recursive formula.

Store computed results.

Avoid re-computation.

Template:

int dp(int n) {
    if (base case) return value;

    if (memo[n] != -1) return memo[n];

    return memo[n] = compute_using_dp(n);
}

B) Bottom-Up (Tabulation)

Build solution iteratively.

Start from base case.

Fill table.

Template:

int[] dp = new int[n+1];
dp[0] = base;
for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    dp[i] = compute_from_previous(dp);
}
return dp[n];

🚀 3. DP Characteristics
✔ 1. Overlapping Subproblems

Example: Fibonacci

f(5)
 ├── f(4)
 │    ├── f(3)
 │    └── f(2)
 └── f(3)


f(3) repeats → DP optimizes it.

✔ 2. Optimal Substructure

Best solution depends on best solution of subparts.

Example:
Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS)

LIS ending at i = 1 + max(LIS ending at j) where j < i and a[j] < a[i]

✔ 3. DP Formulation

Every DP solution consists of:

State definition

Transition/recurrence formula

Base case

Direction (top-down or bottom-up)

Final answer

🚀 4. Examples of DP (Increasing Difficulty)
⭐ Example 1: Fibonacci
Recurrence:
f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-2)

Top-Down:
int[] memo = new int[100];

int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;

    if (memo[n] != 0) return memo[n];

    return memo[n] = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
}

Bottom-Up:
int fib(int n) {
    int[] dp = new int[n+1];
    dp[0] = 0;
    dp[1] = 1;

    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
        dp[i] = dp[i-1] + dp[i-2];

    return dp[n];
}

⭐ Example 2: Climbing Stairs (Ways to Reach nth Step)
dp[n] = dp[n-1] + dp[n-2]


Same as Fibonacci.

⭐ Example 3: Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS)
dp[i] = 1 + max(dp[j]) where j < i and nums[j] < nums[i]

⭐ Example 4: 0/1 Knapsack
State:
dp[i][w] = max value using first i items with capacity w

Recurrence:
if weight[i] > w:
       dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]
else:
       dp[i][w] = max(
                dp[i-1][w],
                value[i] + dp[i-1][w-weight[i]]
       )

⭐ Example 5: Edit Distance (Levenshtein Distance)
Recurrence:
if chars match:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]
else:
    dp[i][j] = 1 + min(
        dp[i-1][j],     // delete
        dp[i][j-1],     // insert
        dp[i-1][j-1]    // replace
    )

🚀 5. DP Patterns (Very Important for Interviews)
💡 Pattern 1: Fibonacci / One-Dimensional DP

Used in:

climbing stairs

decoding ways

house robber

min cost climbing stairs

Identification:

Depends on last few states

Simple recurrence

💡 Pattern 2: 2D DP Table (Matrix)

Used in:

Edit distance

LCS

DP on strings

DP on grids

min path sum

unique paths

Template:

int[][] dp = new int[n+1][m+1];

💡 Pattern 3: DP on Subsets / Bitmask DP

Used in:

traveling salesman

bitmask problems

set-based DP

💡 Pattern 4: Knapsack DP

Used in:

partition equal sum

coin change

subset sum

0/1 knapsack

unbounded knapsack

💡 Pattern 5: DP on Trees

Typical DFS DP:

dp[node] = f(children)


Used in:

diameter of tree

node coloring

tree DP problems on LeetCode

💡 Pattern 6: DP + Binary Search

Used in optimized LIS (O(n log n)).

💡 Pattern 7: DP on Intervals

Used in:

Matrix chain multiplication

Burst balloons

Palindrome partitioning

Formula usually:

dp[l][r] = best of some k between l and r

🚀 6. Steps To Solve ANY DP Problem
1️⃣ Identify state

What are you solving?
Example: dp[i] = LIS ending at i

2️⃣ Define recurrence

How to compute dp?

3️⃣ Base cases

Usually dp[0] or dp[1]

4️⃣ Choose direction (Top-Down or Bottom-Up)
5️⃣ Return answer

dp[n], max(dp), dp[last][last], etc.

🚀 7. DP vs Other Techniques
Technique	When Used
Recursion	Explore all possibilities
Backtracking	Search with prune
Greedy	Locally optimal choices work
Dynamic Programming	Optimal + overlapping problems
Divide & Conquer	Independent subproblems
🚀 8. Common DP Mistakes

❌ Wrong base conditions
❌ Misinterpreting recurrence
❌ Using recursion without memo
❌ Array index out of bounds
❌ Confusing knapsack vs coin change transitions

